WEBVTT

00:00.031 --> 00:01.613
So that's a visual transformer.

00:02.014 --> 00:05.499
Now, what do we do with it in this dyno architecture?

00:05.899 --> 00:07.542
I've already shown you this picture.

00:07.602 --> 00:10.206
Let's go a little bit deeper into that.

00:10.927 --> 00:15.653
Self-supervised learning naturally means you have no labels.

00:15.874 --> 00:22.984
And in this case, you don't even have a negative sample mechanism or a contrastive learning mechanism.

00:22.964 --> 00:32.876
So what you want to do is you want to train a model that sort of gives you, gives you sensible representations.

00:33.717 --> 00:37.182
And that is easier said than done.

00:37.242 --> 00:39.485
If you have no labels.

00:40.526 --> 00:47.014
Now, the, when you do contrastive learning, the goal is that you have an image.

00:48.530 --> 00:55.891
And you just take two patches from the image, let's say, and you have another image, and you take a patch from that.

00:56.713 --> 00:59.380
And now you have what's called your anchor.

00:59.641 --> 01:00.463
This is your anchor.

01:01.165 --> 01:03.552
And then you have patch.

01:03.532 --> 01:17.870
patch A from the same patch B. Now you present the model, all the three patches, and you tell it which one is the anchor, and it needs to decide is the patch A or patch B from the same image.

01:17.950 --> 01:23.397
You can see how this objective can give you a sort of representation because the model learns

01:23.377 --> 01:26.640
what kind of stuff is likely to be in the same image.

01:27.181 --> 01:28.923
This is not the case right here.

01:29.083 --> 01:30.825
We don't do contrastive learning.

01:30.865 --> 01:32.086
We don't have negative samples.

01:32.126 --> 01:38.793
We only, we take one image and then we augment that image in different ways.

01:39.314 --> 01:42.698
Now augmentations are kind of a science by itself.

01:42.938 --> 01:49.505
I think they say they follow the paper BYOL in terms of augmentations.

01:49.645 --> 01:51.527
I've also made a video on that.

01:51.507 --> 02:17.447
Essentially what you do is you do various random perturbations of the image, you might flip it, you might apply some color jitter, you might apply like some solarization, anything like this, anything you can do to make the image different, but that you're relatively sure that, you know, it still looks like the same, like you would still recognize it as the same image.

02:17.427 --> 02:22.313
So a part of these augmentations are also crops.

02:22.734 --> 02:25.618
What I've shown you here are crops of the same image.

02:26.319 --> 02:28.582
They do something special right here.

02:29.443 --> 02:34.169
When they have an image, they crop in two different ways.

02:34.509 --> 02:36.872
One, they call, I think, global crops.

02:37.373 --> 02:42.760
And these are crops which generally cover more than 50% of the image.

02:42.740 --> 02:50.530
Whereas the other ones, they called local crops, and these are crops that cover less than 50% of the image.

02:52.493 --> 02:55.477
This is going to be important in one while.

02:55.497 --> 03:00.723
So these are global and these are local crops of the same image.

03:02.065 --> 03:02.706
So

03:04.053 --> 03:08.061
they exactly and keep that in mind.

03:08.702 --> 03:12.610
And now we have to understand what's up with this student and this teacher.

03:12.670 --> 03:17.640
So what we ideally want to do is we want to have

03:19.645 --> 03:22.249
two different augmentations of the same image.

03:22.269 --> 03:27.679
So here you have an image and you can see we make two different versions of that image.

03:28.119 --> 03:35.592
Now this could be two different crops and then we apply two different color jitters, we apply two different random rotations and so on.

03:35.632 --> 03:39.679
We just want two different versions of the same image.

03:39.659 --> 03:48.293
And our goal finally is going to be here, you can see the loss is that the representation we get out of it is the same.

03:48.414 --> 03:57.449
So we teach the network that look, these two things, they might look different, you know, but they are, in fact, the same.

03:58.310 --> 04:05.903
They are, you know, from their crops, differently augmented, differently cropped, but from the same image.

04:05.883 --> 04:10.037
So the easiest thing would be to just pass the two through

